SIMPLE: stress
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stress
<hw>Stress</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Abbrev. fr.
<ets>distress</ets>; or cf. OF. <ets>estrecier</ets> to press, pinch,
(assumed) LL. <ets>strictiare</ets>, fr. L. <ets>strictus</ets>. See
<er>Distress</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Distress.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sad hersal of his heavy <qex>stress</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Pressure, strain; -- used chiefly of immaterial
things; except in mechanics; hence, urgency; importance; weight;
significance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The faculties of the mind are improved by exercise, yet they must
not be put to a <qex>stress</qex> beyond their strength.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A body may as well lay too little as too much <qex>stress</qex>
upon a dream.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mech. & Physics)</fld> <def>The force, or
combination of forces, which produces a strain; force exerted in any
direction or manner between contiguous bodies, or parts of bodies, and
taking specific names according to its direction, or mode of action, as
<xex>thrust</xex> or <xex>pressure</xex>, <xex>pull</xex> or
<xex>tension</xex>, <xex>shear</xex> or <xex>tangential
stress</xex>.</def> <rj><au>Rankine.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Stress</qex> is the mutual action between portions of
matter.</q> <rj><qau>Clerk Maxwell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Pron.)</fld> <def>Force of utterance expended upon
words or syllables. Stress is in English the chief element in accent and
is one of the most important in emphasis. See <cref>Guide to
pronunciation</cref>, ⟦sect⟧⟦sect⟧ 31-35.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Scots Law)</fld> <def>Distress; the act of
distraining; also, the thing distrained.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stress of voice</b></col>, <cd>unusual exertion of the
voice.</cd> -- <col><b>Stress of weather</b></col>, <cd>constraint
imposed by continued bad weather; <as>as, to be driven back to port by
<ex>stress of weather</ex></as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To lay stress
upon</b></col>, <cd>to attach great importance to; to emphasize.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧Consider how great a <xex>stress</xex> is <xex>laid upon</xex>
this duty.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Atterbury.</au> -- <mcol><col><b>To put stress
upon</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>To put to a stress</b></col></mcol>,
<cd>to strain.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1425 --></p>

<p><ent>Stress</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stress
<hw>Stress</hw> <pr>(str⟦ecr⟧s)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To press; to urge; to distress; to put to difficulties.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To subject to stress, pressure, or strain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To subject to phonetic stress; to accent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To place emphasis on; to make emphatic;
emphasize.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stressful</ent>⟦br⟧
